description.text:
TL;DR:
Clothespin with a hook.

The weather forecast predicted >>35°C (that's >95°F :-), so I bought a few meters of the cheapest, yet lightproof curtain fabric I could find and created these hooks for hanging them up.
After doing so, I found hundreds of other possibilities to use them...

The Clothespin Hook is compatible to the most (tm) commercially available clothespins, and well, you'll need one of those springs...

But instead of throwing away both wooden/plastics parts, please consider only printing the "...R.stl" file and resusing the existing one.
The remaining, unused part can be thrown in one of your children's rooms. A perfect opportunity to stir things up... m/
Coque pour telephone Xperia Z1 (Grand modèle) avec suport retractable pour poser l'appareil en position inclinée et 3 slots pour carte Micro SD.

Vous aurez besoin de :

  • 3 aiguilles a coudre (diamètre 0,6 mm).
  • Un Dremel ou équivalent, muni d'un disque a tronçonner.
  • Un mini chalumeau ou un briquet.
  • Une petite lime.
  • Une petite pince.
  • Colle contact (type cyanoacrylate).

Pour le montage proprement dit se référer a la vidéo YouTube :
https://youtu.be/80MvhUYjXoQ

Préparation :

  • Tronçonner 6 morceaux de 18 mm de long a partir des trois aiguilles a coudre (évitez la pointe et le chat, servez vous de la partie centrale).
  • Ajustez si besoin le pivot de chaque pièce articulée avec une petite lime.
  • Pour introduire les axes dans les pièces plastique, chauffez les juste un peu en les tenant avec une petite pince. Puis insérer a chaud.
  • Avant de coller, vérifiez aussi les logements pour carte MicroSD, ajuster si besoin.

description.text: This is a model for the Spyro from the game The legend of Spyro: Dawn of the Dragon. The design is of French origin. I have repaired the wings and tested the print out, Now working on painting it. Will have more pictures of it painted soon.

This was printed on an XYZ Da Vinci 2.0 Duo, In ABS plastic. It was sliced using the XYZware, with medium level support material. The one shown was scaled by 0.5 from the original file to make it fit the print bed. It used 11m of filament. Be careful when removing support material of any type as the legs have an alarming tendency to snap off, The one shown had two of it's legs come off, but they were seamlessly reattached with a dab of super glue. I would recommend having some super glue ready for the support removal process as the legs coming off is very likely. Glues back together perfectly and you can't tell the difference once repaired. Watch the wings as well as they are very long, thin and broad.

title: Kossel Mini Offset Top Mounted Filament Spool Holder

description.text:
I Like the top mounted Kossel spool holders I have seen on thingiverse, but since I mounted my extruder on top and I have some spools that are larger in diameter like those from Hatchbox, I needed to offset the center spindle toward the front of the printer in order for the spool to clear my extruder. Like elmuchcho (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:371881), I used a 3.5" HD bearing. Mine is from an old Maxtor HD.

I borrowed the spindle and centering cone ideas from the CreativeTools design. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:508896

I wanted to be able to keep the spool as close to the printers aluminum frame as possible, so the support brackets are designed in 2 parts to allow the triangular frame to sit lower inside the aluminum frame and still be printed in an orientation that doesn't expose it to delamination under the weight of the filament.

I hope someone finds this helpful. Please let me know any suggestions for changes to the design. I'm happy with how mine is working now so I probably wont redesign it, but I'm always interested in how others would do things differently.

You need one of everything except b1 you need two of those. I used socket head cap screws and nuts that fit my 1515 extrusions. the spindle is designed with support in the model so it should be printed without support. depending on the make and model HD you cannibalize for your bearing you will probably need to adjust the dimensions of the opening on the bottom of the spindle and the hole that it sits in on the frame a1.

title: Customizable Extruder Groove Mount v3 with Servo

description.text:
This is the third and probably the final version of the extruder mount. that I made to accommodate the groove mount or to fit in j-head and e3d mount style.

This is an improvement of the previous version with an option to pick which mounting screw you want. There are 3 types of mount screws to fasten your extruder:

  1. Original design - uses 4 screws
  2. Geeetech plate - 2 m4 screws, at most would be 16mm in length
  3. Greg's Wade - This one based on the Greg's wade reloaded found here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18379

There are also servo option but can only be used with original design that uses fastener because it is slotted on top of it. The servo only fit for sg9 type servo aka tower pro servo. I didn't design the arm yet because I'm considering to use inductive sensor

The model included here are all have screw mounts for all types of extruder mount, and there will be at least 8 screw holes and all uses m4 screws.

I'm making this available on https://github.com/sarf2k4/Customizable-GTech-Parts too so that you guys able to make more presets

You don't have to recalibrate the x and y max/offset limit with this (for geeetech users) and this one is a compact design that tries to maximize the print volume on all 3 axis

I've fitted my e3d v6 here https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bqfmADIjP2k&list=PLb7sKitt_N_CRhatUqbEtEncIshFv4Ro6&index=2

Update 5/8/2015:
Inductive sensor add-on here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:956051

The stl files here are all fit for geeetech x carriage with all mounting hole options enabled with m4 screws for all of them

Download the zip file to customize these to your liking and the comments inside the scad script should be self explanatory

The servo mount is only for mk8 extruder/kistruder and fastener from original design, because the original design, using the original mk8(with fan and heatsink) screw (long) that will go through the fastener then fastened on to the mount base with another 4 screws from the bottom.

This is a spool holder to use for inside of a spool container. I used a Snapware Airtight With Handle Large 40 Cup 10X8X9. Amazon usually has it for ~$15. You can mount of these on each side to hold up a cut to length 1" PVC pipe to use a sealed spool holder. Throw in some silica gel or something to suck out moisture. Use M3 bolts to screw into it.

I was angry at myself for being unable to find my Mag-Lite during a recent power outage. Thanks to my Replicator 2, that'll never happen again! This thing is a permanent bracket to hold a D-cell Mag-Lite flashlight; the next time you need your trusty flashlight, you'll know exactly where it is.
This bracket is fixed to the wall with (3) flat-head wood screws.

I printed on a Rep 2 with a raft, no supports. Infill and layer resolution is up to you; most settings should work just fine.
As long as your screws are flat-headed, you should have no problem affixing this thing to any vertical surface in your home.

So the next time a droid, that we need measurements from, shows up in public, you can take the tool out of your pack, point, 2 clicks... slide, read the measurement & report back.

title: heatsink and support for extruder hot end.

description.text:
I've been playing with a lot of extruder hot end designs, I've been through every design I could put together for 3mm. One common issue is heat dissipation above the nozzle. Whether the filament is getting too hot too high up or the insulating barrel is too hot for the filament block, I wanted to design a heatsink that could fit the most common designs. While I was at it I figured having optional support bolts would help as well. They don't line up with anything that currently exists but that's easily remedied.
The intention is for this to be metal cast in an investment process.
I'm curious about how much heat it could dissipate if it were just used in PLA form.

They have many differences between them, but I seem to get the best extrusion quality from my http://arcol.huarcol.hu one. I don't know exactly why my results are much better with it, but that extruder takes a lot of care in colling till the last second, so that's the best I can come up with so far. This idea is to cool thee insulator, not the brass so I don't see any harm in cooling it. Especially since the majority of hot end failures are related to the insulator barrel getting hot and warping / failing.

title: Zallus Reflow Controller Case, with mounting brackets and bezel

description.text:
The Zallus reflow controller is a board used to convert a conventional toaster oven into a solder reflow oven for assembling electronics. This is far and away the most well done controller of it's type I've seen; using a color touch screen display and an optional USB-connected PC app.

There are two other cases for the Zallus on Thingiverse, here, and here; but one has mounting brackets and no bezel, and the other has a bezel but no brackets. This has both, and some loops in the back that might be useful for cable management.

This case is for the Rev 2 controller.

This thing actually started with the case given as a .stl on the Zallus website. I did nothing to the actual case, and the design is totally his, used here with his permission. The mounting legs were done in OpenSCAD and added to the case with MeshMixer. The bezel was also done in OpenSCAD.

If you drill out the holes in the case with a 7/64" drill, an M3 screw will tap into it nicely. I used four M3-15 socket head cap screws, and the heads inset nicely into the bezel.

description.text:
A snap on adapter to allow upgrade from threaded rod to Lead Screws.
I got 2 of these from Amazon.com
(http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00PXIEK50?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o07_s00)
also grabbed a pair of these
(http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00H1LNX5A?psc=1&redirect=true&ref_=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00)
since the Lead Screw is slightly thicker than the Threaded Rod that came with the MakerGear Prusa Mendel Kit. Also needed 8x #4 x3/8in Pan head screws.
I now have much smoother Z axis motion and I didn't have to remove more than the 2 Z axis stepper motors and threaded rod to install the replacement.

You may need to use a drill bit to remove some plastic from inside the part the threaded rod went through since the lead screw is slightly thicker. I used a 3/8" in bit and it worked great. I didn't use a drill just the bit and a hand drill.

HOW IT'S MADE:
Designed this cracked flower pot using multiple 3d programs:
In 3ds Max I modeled the basic forms like the pieces of the pot, the forming of the roots around the pieces and a cell so that everything will stay together and so the pot can still hold water.
To make sure the pieces of the pot and the shell were solid I used Dynamesh in Zbrush.
The details on the roots I did by sculpting in Mudbox. After that I brought the detailed roots back to max together with the pot from Zbrush so I could export it for Slicing in Cura.

The Print that is showed in the pictures was printed on a Ultimaker2 at 0.2mm layerhight ABS. After around 13 hours the print was done.
Before painting I done some sanding and used XTC-3D to smooth out the seems. I could also use accitone but that was more unstable and tricky to get a good result.

Painting i did in about 3 staps:
First I painted an base color with airbrush, in this case i used gray. The next layer was the flat coloring with airbrush of pot and the roots with paint a brush.
At last I used lightly the airbrush for accentuating the details and a little bit of ambient occlusion.

title: #CatchTheWind > Charge your Phone > Vertical Wind Turbine Generator

description.text:
In Spirit of the competition > I wanted to make something useful ..... and started with the goal of charging my iPhone using the power of the wind.

Immediately a turbine comes to mind.
This Vertical Turbine will drive a generator and then charge small DC devices.

I wanted to make it portable, you can take it anywhere and charge your phone.

It is magnetically levitated. The repelling magnets will handle the weight of the Rotor. Let the wind make it Turn and generate electricity.

I can add another generator section. i.e Magnet Rotor with Coils.

Things still to consider

The Turbine >
Many different designs
how many blades should i use ?
Reading up on Wikipedia - i might change the Turbine.

The Generator >
The current design uses round coils.
I might change this to use pie shaped winding's instead.

Will update on progress as i go along.

There is only one company that is selling Makerbot Machine's here in South Africa (Rectron) - I went past last week and was blown away. Makerbot is amazing.

Update : 2015-07-06
I wanted to start the Build on the weekend.
I have run into a horrible problem .. this build I made to be the maximum size possible for my printer.
While the model shows in the center of the print bed the actual print is not and Prints off the heated bed. ?!?

I don't know why this is happening - anyone run into a similar problem please let me know.
I will sort this during the course of the week and aim to print this weekend.

Update : 2015-07-09
I had to change my original design. Its a bit smaller now.
uploaded new Files for this. I have printed the base and the coil Base and the Coils. (Uploaded Pics and new STL Files)

Will Start the winding Tonight. :(:

Update : 2015-07-13
Productive sessions this weekend.

Changed the Coil design so i could attach them to a drill
(winding the coils by hand would have taken 45 years)
Changed the Magnet Rotor, nicer design i printed and completed the original one (Pic Attached) but will reprint new design
Designed a back cover for the coil base (for all the wiring etc)

Printed the Turbine (Pic Uploaded) (15 hour Print !?)
Printed 6 coils and wound them.

coming together nicely

Update : 2015-07-14
Printed new Rotor
my printer is not closing off the Top layer 100 % now ?
I increased the extrusion rate by 2 % to correct this - if anyone knows why - please let me know.
Pics of the coil winding are up too.

Update : 2015-07-21
Printer has been giving me problems - have to leave it alone for a bit then give it some love. Its weird . Prints perfectly ! then not.

its printing great again - printed the Coil Base Cover
See pics

The Coils are hurting me , I keep dropping them / breaking them.
The thickness of the coil prints is not strong enough for so much wire. if your printing these make sure they are 100 % infill otherwise just don't manhandle them be gentle.

I broke 4 - reprinted with 100 % infill

The Turbine Blade - I was testing my design with a fan . It Does work but can be much better,
I am going to change the Blade
it will use 3 Blades instead of 6 and will print 1 mm thick sheets for the blades.

I have added a Pic of where i am so far.
Going from Thought to product : - designing something and making it is a process. I never saw so many changes coming but until you put it together you wont know.

I designed this using Autodesk Inventor
i have a Prusa i3 ( LH 0.2 Nozzle 0.4 PLA 1.75mm)

Part List
Base
Coil Base (x2)
Coil Base Cover (x2)
Turbine
Rotor
5mm Carbon Tube (From local RC shop)
Magnets 30 mm x 5 mm (x8)
Magnet Wire 0.28mm

Making the Coils
Print the Coil base and the Cover - Glue them together.
NB : Print the Coils with 100 % infill
Use a drill to wind the coil then I used clear Nail Polish to coat the winding and put some insulation tape on.
Cut the Additional piece off (Used to attach to the drill)
Coil is ready to Go. (See Pics)

title: Garden hose connector x4 adapter for 1/4" irrigation tubing

description.text:
This is a male garden hose connector on one end, four 1/4" connectors on the other end. They fit 1/4" irrigation tubing snugly. This is improved over my first version, since it has "ears" that will allow you to twist the connector into its companion without twisting off the 1/4" parts. It also has significant reinforcement for the 1/4" connectors themselves, since they are subject to bending forces in common garden use. Note this is the opposite style of connector than you would expect; I had a situation where I needed this particular style, so here it is. Then again if you have a hydroponic or irrigation system made of printed parts, you don't have to stick to conventions of what style connector goes where.

After using this myself for several weeks, I have some suggestions for real-world use. I use Rain Bird 1/4" irrigation tubing, which fits quite snugly, and also tends to constrict after you spread it out. Take a medium-sized Phillips-head screwdriver and spread out the first 1/2" or so length of tubing, then force it on the 1/4" portion of the x4 adapter. It will naturally return to something close to its original size, and fit quite nicely with no leaks. Ideally the tubing should go all the way to the bottom of the 1/4" pieces. The tops of the 1/4" portions are still a bit thin; I could reduce the hole size a bit and increase the strength, but if you follow my advice and push the tubing all the way down, you won't have any issues with the those pieces snapping off. Also, make sure you use a rubber ring between this and the mating part; most hoses have this built in, but if you're matching it to another 3D printed part, you will need to add it.

Also, I have added a second file, mm3impghc1x4.stl, which I have ran through MeshMixer. Some people have had an issue with slicer errors. Try this one if you have an issue. Also, you might try the "short" version of this same item, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1498649, to see if it gives you the same issues.
Printed four-nozzle-side-up in PLA at 230 degrees, needs no support.

This is the sixth revision of my magnetic separation stand, re-designed to efficiently use cheap 8mm by 2mm rare earth magnets (center wall is angled to meet the angle of a 1.5 mL tube, in order to bring the magnets closer to the tube. The benefit is that you can use a cheaper magnet, if you are willing to only use 1. 5mL microfuge tubes). You could very easily use double the amount of 8mm by 1mm magnets (http://dx.com/p/super-strong-rare-earth-re-magnets-8mm-20-pack-4248 and through other places. I got my 8mmX2mm magnets at Harbor Freight, although these aren't the ones they sell online). This stand separates beads at the same rate as my Promega stand (http://tinyurl.com/bqcnefq), but instead of $45 this stand cost me $3 to make (including the magnets). You can print off multiples of this unit or you can redesign it to accommodate more than two microfuge tubes, or 2 mL tubes. Cheers!

Print this off (upside down, with no supports on my Replicator 2).  I probably used 3 shells and 35% infill.  Insert magnets (they will actually attract each other and hold each other inside the plastic stand).  Then, purify proteins!
